properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A frontal system west of the offshore waters over the Pacific will be rapidly intensifying today as it approaches the BC coast. As the frontal system reaches the BC north and central coasts later today and overnight into Monday it rapidly moves south. By Monday afternoon the system stalls over west Vancouver Island and upwards of 100 to 150 mm of rainfall accumulation could occur through until Tuesday morning. Over the south coast, the frontal system will become entrenched overnight Monday and through until Tuesday afternoon. During that time, accumulations of 50 to 75 mm could be expected to fall over north and central metro Vancouver regions as well as Howe Sound. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A disturbance forecast to intensify over eastern Canada will track northeastward and lie over the Labrador Sea by Tuesday morning. Snow and strong winds associated with this system will move into southeastern Baffin Island Monday night and by Tuesday morning north to northwest winds gusting to 80 km/h or higher are expected. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snow is expected. Total snowfall: 20 to 40 cm with higher amounts possible. Locations: central Labrador, Groswater Bay to the north Labrador coast. Time span: Monday through Tuesday afternoon. Remarks: Rain or snow will begin over most areas by early Monday morning then transition to snow later in the day or Monday evening and persist into Tuesday morning. Conditions will improve by Tuesday afternoon. In addition strong northerlies will develop Monday evening causing reduced visibility in blowing snow over exposed areas. Please monitor your local forecast for future updates. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions, significant snowfall and very cold wind chill values beginning late this afternoon or early evening. A vigorous Pacific frontal system will arrive late this afternoon or early evening bringing with it significant snowfall and strong winds resulting in blizzard conditions. Blizzard conditions will last through Monday with total snowfall accumulations up to 60 cm. The strong winds will also produce very cold wind chill values near -30. ### Travel is expected to be very difficult or impossible due to near-zero visibility. Road closures are possible. properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A prolonged period of snow, ice pellets, and freezing rain is expected to begin late Sunday afternoon and end Monday afternoon. The heaviest snow is expected to fall near the Alberta-N.W.T. border, with total accumulations of 10-15 cm possible. A persistent band of freezing rain and ice pellets is expected to form south of the snow. There is uncertainty on the exact location of the band of freezing rain, but current indications suggest it will be mainly south of Highway 58. Freezing rain amounts will be highly variable, but could range from 1-5 mm. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
